{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cb008cb6-3f68-4b42-889b-5f42011f8a64","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can give you the exact configuration needed. To publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool**, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Required for NuGet.org -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key properties:**\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType` | Must be `Exe` (should already be set for a console app) |\n\n**Publish steps:**\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install & run with:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nNo special MCP-specific packaging is needed — since it uses stdio transport, it works as a standard dotnet tool executable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f6c77262-eab6-4dee-a34e-79f8e32ac5d2","outputTokens":495,"requestId":"D01C:3509D7:154B651:17CDF24:6A067497"},"id":"7073dbe7-a3e0-4148-b7b4-4b49bbe55fd9","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:19:28.540Z","parentId":"609f3299-14d0-44c9-b3b8-f3c16b51c97a"}
